1. Project Description
What I Am Building
This project is my personal homepage. It is a digital portfolio that showcases who I am, what I have built, and where I am headed in my career. The goal was to create a clean and professional space where someone can quickly understand my background without needing to dig through LinkedIn or ask me for a resume.
The site highlights my education, work experience, technical skills, and real projects that I have worked on. It also includes a short article page where I share my thoughts on web development trends. Everything is built using vanilla HTML, CSS, and JavaScript with no frameworks.
Why I Am Building It
I am currently a graduate student at Northeastern University. Before this, I worked as a Software Engineer at LTIMindtree and co founded an ed tech startup called FastFindFirm. I realized that I did not have one central place to present all of this experience in a clear and personal way.
LinkedIn is useful, but it limits how much personality and depth you can show. A personal website gives me full control over how I tell my story. It also serves as a long term portfolio that I can keep improving as I grow in my career.
On a practical level, every developer is expected to have some form of portfolio site today. This project helps me stand out when applying for internships, full time roles, or networking with people in the industry.
Target Audience
The main people I expect to visit this site are:
Recruiters and hiring managers who want to evaluate me for internships or full time roles
 Other developers who may want to collaborate or see what I have built
 Professors and classmates who want to learn more about my background
 People I meet at networking events who want a simple link to my work
What Makes It Different
The assignment required a creative differentiating feature. I implemented animated skill bars that trigger when the skills section scrolls into view. The bars smoothly animate from zero percent to their target values, and the numbers count up at the same time.
I also added a few interactive touches to make the site feel more dynamic and polished:
Navigation dots on the side of the homepage for quick section jumping
 Hover effects on project cards
 A filter system on the projects page
 Smooth scrolling for internal links
These features are not just decorative. They show that I understand JavaScript, browser APIs, and how to build small interactive components from scratch.

